<node id="2FA">
  <data key="d0">2FA</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) is a security process that requires users to provide two different authentication factors to verify their identity. It is primarily used for securing user accounts and access, ensuring an additional layer of protection beyond traditional single-factor methods like passwords. 2FA is implemented as a mechanism within systems to enhance security, often with specific visibility or enforcement tailored for internal users. The method commonly involves email-based one-time codes sent to users as a secondary verification step, though other factors (such as SMS codes, authenticator apps, or biometric data) may also be used depending on the system's configuration. Its purpose is to mitigate unauthorized access and safeguard sensitive data by adding a second layer of authentication, thereby reducing the risk of breaches stemming from compromised credentials alone.</data>
  <data key="d3">doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-029&lt;SEP&gt;doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-062&lt;SEP&gt;doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-063&lt;SEP&gt;doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-001&lt;SEP&gt;doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-044&lt;SEP&gt;doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-004&lt;SEP&gt;doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-005&lt;SEP&gt;doc-fb57212021fb1e5e7a76ae882be19321-chunk-027</data>
  <data key="d4">LizardDocu.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1781356274</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
